<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<!DOCTYPE plist PUBLIC "-//Apple//DTD PLIST 1.0//EN" "http://www.apple.com/DTDs/PropertyList-1.0.dtd">
<!--
  Hardened-runtime entitlements for the Developer ID signed + notarized release
  (used by electron-builder.config.cjs as BOTH `mac.entitlements` and
  `mac.entitlementsInherit`, so the helper/utility processes — the fastembed
  embedding worker and the Tesseract OCR worker — inherit them too).

  Only meaningful when `hardenedRuntime: true`, i.e. INTERLEAVE_RELEASE_SIGN=1.
  The ad-hoc dev build does NOT enable hardened runtime and does not use this file.

  Why exactly these two keys (and nothing else):

  - com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit — REQUIRED. V8 / Electron need JIT-compiled
    executable memory; on arm64 with Electron 20+ the app crashes at launch under
    hardened runtime without it.

  - com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation — REQUIRED here. We load
    PREBUILT native addons that are NOT signed with our Team ID:
    `native/better_sqlite3.node`, the `onnxruntime` `.node`/`.dylib` shipped with
    `fastembed`, and the Tesseract worker. Library validation forces every
    dynamically-loaded Mach-O to share the host's Team ID, so it would refuse to
    load them and the app would crash. This is the same entitlement VS Code,
    Cursor, and Obsidian ship for the same reason.

  Deliberately OMITTED:
  - com.apple.security.cs.allow-unsigned-executable-memory — only needed on
    Electron <= 11; we're on Electron 39, where it only widens the attack surface.
    FALLBACK: if a helper process crashes under hardened runtime, add it here.
  - debugger / dyld-environment-variables / apple-events / network — not needed by
    this app; each one weakens the hardened runtime, so we don't copy-paste them.
-->
<plist version="1.0">
<dict>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.allow-jit</key>
  <true/>
  <key>com.apple.security.cs.disable-library-validation</key>
  <true/>
</dict>
</plist>
